TY  - JOUR
AU  - Rob, Rafael
AU  - Vettas, Nikolaos
T1  - Foreign Direct Investment and Exports with Growing Demand
PY  - 2003
Y1  - 2003/07/01
DO  - 10.1111/1467-937X.00259
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 70
IS  - 3
SP  - 629
EP  - 648
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We explore entry into a foreign market with uncertain demand growth. A multinational can serve the foreign demand by two modes, or by a combination thereof: it can export its products, or it can create productive capacity via foreign direct investment (FDI). The advantage of FDI is that it allows for lower marginal cost than exporting does. The disadvantage is that FDI is irreversible and, hence, entails the risk of creating under-utilized capacity in the case that the market turns out to be small. The presence of demand uncertainty and irreversibility gives rise to an interior solution, where the multinational, under certain conditions, both exports its products and does FDI.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1467-937X.00259
ER  - 



